  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The titles \"Ms.,\" \"Mrs.,\" and \"Miss\" are used as honorifics to address or refer to women, and each has a slightly different usage:\n\n1. **Miss**: This title is traditionally used for unmarried women. It is often applied to younger women or girls, but it can be used for any unmarried woman regardless of age.\n\n2. **Mrs.**: This title is used for married women. It is commonly followed by the husband\u2019s last name (e.g., Mrs. Smith). Some women continue to use \"Mrs.\" with their own last name as well, often after they've married.\n\n3. **Ms.**: This is a neutral title that does not imply marital status. It can be used for any woman, married or unmarried. Many women prefer \"Ms.\" because it does not denote their marital status and is seen as more modern and egalitarian.\n\nIn professional or formal settings, if you're unsure of a woman\u2019s marital status, it is generally safest to use \"Ms.\" unless you are directly instructed otherwise.",
